---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import CodeSnippet from '../components/CodeSnippet.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import { SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_TITLE } from '../consts';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<BaseHead title={SITE_TITLE} description={SITE_DESCRIPTION} />
	</head>
	<body>
		<Header />
		<main class="landing">
			<section class="hero">
				<p class="eyebrow">Global protocols for multi-agent LLM systems</p>
				<h1>Write one global protocol. Run deadlock-free agents.</h1>
				<p class="hero-copy">
					Building multi-agent systems is hard because coordination logic ends up scattered across
					agent prompts, callbacks, and state machines no one fully understands. ZipperGen gives
					you a single global protocol: who sends what to whom, who runs which LLM, and who owns
					each decision — including tools, humans, and external services. ZipperGen projects it
					to each agent automatically and runs it concurrently.
				</p>
				<div class="hero-actions">
					<a class="button primary" href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/zippergen">View on GitHub</a>
					<a class="button secondary" href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.17612">Read the paper</a>
					<a href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/paper-isola/tree/main/Lean">
						<img src="/lean-formalized.svg" alt="Lean formalized" height="34" />
					</a>
					<a href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/paper-isola/tree/main/Lean">
						<img src="/lean.svg" alt="Lean verified" height="34" />
					</a>
				</div>
				<p class="trust-note">Core projection theorems machine-checked in Lean 4.</p>
				<figure class="hero-shot">
					<img
						src="/zipperchat-screenshot.png"
						alt="ZipperChat showing a live per-lifeline event feed for a workflow execution"
					/>
				</figure>
			</section>

			<section class="feature-grid" aria-label="Core properties">
				<article>
					<h2>Global first</h2>
					<p>Write the coordination once as a protocol instead of scattering it across agent prompts and callbacks.</p>
				</article>
				<article>
					<h2>Projected locally</h2>
					<p>Each lifeline receives the local program it needs: sends, receives, owned decisions, tool calls, and optional human control points.</p>
				</article>
				<article>
					<h2>Deadlock-free</h2>
					<p>If the workflow compiles, the coordination layer is structurally deadlock-free by construction.</p>
				</article>
			</section>

			<section class="split-section">
				<div>
					<p class="section-label">Tiny workflow</p>
					<h2>Branching has an owner.</h2>
					<p>
						The annotation <code>@ Editor</code> says that Editor owns the decision. ZipperGen
						generates the control communication needed by the other lifelines.
					</p>
				</div>
				<CodeSnippet
					code={`@workflow
def write_tweet(topic: str @ User) -> str:
    User(topic) >> Writer(topic)
    Writer: tweet = draft(topic)
    Writer(tweet) >> Editor(tweet)
    Editor: approved = approve(tweet)

    if approved @ Editor:
        Editor(tweet) >> User(tweet)
    else:
        Editor(tweet) >> Writer(tweet)
        Writer: tweet = revise(tweet)
        Writer(tweet) >> User(tweet)

    return tweet @ User`}
				/>
			</section>

			<section class="split-section">
				<div>
					<p class="section-label">Larger example</p>
					<h2>Two event loops, shared agents, no routing code.</h2>
					<p>
						<code>command_center.py</code> runs two independent loops in parallel. One handles
						incoming email: <code>Mailbox</code> polls the inbox, <code>Dispatcher</code> classifies
						each message, and fragments handle scheduling, cancellations, tasks, and replies.
						The other handles Telegram commands from the owner. <code>Calendar</code>,
						<code>Writer</code>, and <code>User</code> are shared between both streams.
						ZipperGen's projection ensures each receives exactly the messages it needs, from
						whichever stream generated them, in the order the protocol requires.
					</p>
					<p>
						Run it with mock data to see both streams live without any API keys:
					</p>
					<CodeSnippet lang="bash" code={`python examples/command_center.py --mock`} />
				</div>
				<CodeSnippet
					code={`@workflow
def command_center():
    with parallel:
        with branch:
            while True @ Mailbox:
                if mail_present() @ Mailbox:
                    Mailbox: email = pop_pending_email()
                    Mailbox(email) >> Dispatcher(email)
                    Dispatcher: route = classify_email(email)
                    Dispatcher: route = normalize_route(route)

                    if (route == "spam") @ Dispatcher:
                        ...
                    elif (route == "scheduling") @ Dispatcher:
                        scheduling_branch(email)
                    elif (route == "task") @ Dispatcher:
                        task_branch(email)
                        reply_branch(email)
                    else:
                        reply_branch(email)
                else:
                    Mailbox: _ = wait_briefly()

        with branch:
            while True @ Chat:
                if chat_present() @ Chat:
                    Chat: chat_msg = pop_pending_chat()
                    Chat(chat_msg) >> Dispatcher(chat_msg)
                    Dispatcher: chat_route = classify_chat(chat_msg)
                    Dispatcher: chat_route = normalize_route(chat_route)

                    if (chat_route == "schedule_meeting") @ Dispatcher:
                        schedule_meeting_from_chat(chat_msg)
                    elif (chat_route == "create_task") @ Dispatcher:
                        create_task_from_chat(chat_msg)
                    ...
                else:
                    Chat: _ = wait_briefly()`}
				/>
			</section>

			<section class="bands">
				<div>
					<h2>Causal runtime guards</h2>
					<p>
						When locally received data can be stale, guards can read the latest causally visible
						state instead of a sequential log. Vector clocks and message-carried views make the
						guard result depend on the asynchronous communication structure.
					</p>
					<CodeSnippet
						code={`latest_device_on = At[Device].on == True

if latest_device_on @ Indicator:
    ...`}
					/>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h2>Parallel regions</h2>
					<p>
						Parallel regions run several sub-programs concurrently. Shared lifelines interleave
						their branch-local programs, and branch-specific channels preserve FIFO order where it matters.
					</p>
					<CodeSnippet
						code={`with parallel:
    with branch:
        Orchestrator(candidate) >> TestRunner(candidate)
        TestRunner: (test_status,) = run_tests(candidate)
        TestRunner(test_status) >> Committer(test_status)

    with branch:
        Orchestrator(candidate) >> Security(candidate)
        Security: (security_status,) = scan_security(candidate)
        Security(security_status) >> Committer(security_status)`}
					/>
				</div>
			</section>

			<section class="quick-start">
				<div>
					<p class="section-label">Try it locally</p>
					<h2>No service required for the first examples.</h2>
					<p>
						The built-in mock backend returns placeholder model outputs, so examples can be run
						without API keys. Switch to OpenAI, Mistral, or Claude with one configuration line
						when you want real model calls. ZipperGen can also use OpenAI-compatible local model
						servers such as vLLM; the repository includes a small local Qwen/vLLM example.
					</p>
				</div>
				<CodeSnippet
					lang="bash"
					code={`git clone https://github.com/zippergen-io/zippergen.git
cd zippergen
pip install -e .

python examples/hello.py                 # two lifelines, one LLM call
python examples/command_center.py --mock # email triage + Telegram commands
python examples/parallel.py              # fan-out / fan-in across branches`}
				/>
			</section>

			<section class="formal-section">
				<p class="section-label">Formal foundation</p>
				<h2>Based on Message Sequence Charts.</h2>
				<p>
					The projection from a global protocol to per-agent local programs is syntax-directed,
					and deadlock-freedom follows by structural induction; no runtime checking required.
					The core theorems are in the paper and machine-checked in Lean 4.
				</p>
				<p>
					Bollig, Függer, Nowak. <em>Provable Coordination for LLM Agents via Message Sequence Charts.</em>
					<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2604.17612">arXiv:2604.17612 [cs.PL]</a>
				</p>
				<p>
					Bollig. <em>Causal Past Logic for Runtime Verification of Distributed LLM Agent Workflows.</em>
					<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.20923">arXiv:2605.20923 [cs.LO]</a>
				</p>
			</section>

			<section class="cta-section">
				<h2>Build inspectable agent workflows.</h2>
				<p>
					Start from the examples, inspect the generated message sequence chart, and decide whether
					global protocols fit your agent system.
				</p>
				<div class="hero-actions">
					<a class="button primary" href="https://github.com/zippergen-io/zippergen">Get the code</a>
					<a class="button secondary" href="/about">About the project</a>
				</div>
			</section>
		</main>
		<Footer />
	</body>
</html>

<style>
	.landing {
		width: 100%;
		max-width: none;
		padding: 0;
	}

	.landing :global(pre) {
		margin: 0;
	}

	.hero,
	.feature-grid,
	.split-section,
	.bands,
	.quick-start,
	.formal-section,
	.cta-section {
		width: min(1120px, calc(100% - 2rem));
		margin: 0 auto;
	}

	.hero {
		padding: 5.5rem 0 3rem;
	}

	.eyebrow,
	.section-label {
		margin: 0 0 0.75rem;
		color: var(--accent-dark);
		font-size: 0.82rem;
		font-weight: 700;
		letter-spacing: 0;
		text-transform: uppercase;
	}

	.hero h1 {
		max-width: 850px;
		margin: 0;
		font-size: clamp(2.15rem, 5vw, 4.25rem);
		line-height: 1.02;
	}

	.hero-copy {
		max-width: 760px;
		margin: 1.35rem 0 0;
		color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
		font-size: 1.16rem;
		line-height: 1.65;
	}

	.hero-actions {
		display: flex;
		flex-wrap: wrap;
		gap: 0.75rem;
		align-items: center;
		margin-top: 1.6rem;
	}

	.button {
		display: inline-flex;
		align-items: center;
		justify-content: center;
		min-height: 2.75rem;
		padding: 0 1.1rem;
		border-radius: 6px;
		font-weight: 600;
		text-decoration: none;
	}

	.button.primary {
		background: rgb(var(--black));
		color: white;
	}

	.button.secondary {
		border: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray), 0.28);
		background: white;
		color: rgb(var(--black));
	}

	.hero-actions img {
		display: block;
		border-radius: 0;
	}

	.trust-note {
		margin: 0.75rem 0 0;
		color: rgb(var(--gray));
		font-size: 0.9rem;
	}

	.hero-shot {
		margin: 3rem 0 0;
	}

	.hero-shot img {
		display: block;
		width: 100%;
		border: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray), 0.2);
		border-radius: 8px;
		box-shadow: 0 22px 55px rgba(19, 31, 45, 0.12);
	}

	.feature-grid {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
		gap: 1rem;
		padding: 1rem 0 3rem;
	}

	.feature-grid article {
		border: 1px solid rgba(var(--gray), 0.18);
		border-radius: 8px;
		background: white;
		padding: 1.15rem;
	}

	.feature-grid h2,
	.bands h2,
	.quick-start h2,
	.formal-section h2,
	.cta-section h2,
	.split-section h2 {
		font-size: clamp(1.7rem, 4vw, 2.6rem);
	}

	.feature-grid h2 {
		margin-bottom: 0.4rem;
		font-size: 1.25rem;
	}

	.feature-grid p,
	.bands p,
	.quick-start p,
	.formal-section p,
	.cta-section p,
	.split-section p {
		color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
	}

	.split-section,
	.quick-start {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 0.78fr) minmax(0, 1.22fr);
		gap: 2rem;
		align-items: start;
		padding: 4rem 0 2rem;
	}


	.bands {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
		gap: 1.25rem;
		padding: 4rem 0;
	}

	.bands > div {
		border-radius: 8px;
		background: #f8fafc;
		padding: 1.35rem;
	}

	.bands .code-snippet {
		margin-top: 1rem;
	}

	.formal-section,
	.cta-section {
		padding: 4rem 0;
	}

	.formal-section {
		padding-bottom: 2rem;
	}

	.formal-section p,
	.cta-section p {
		max-width: 760px;
	}

	.cta-section {
		padding-bottom: 5rem;
	}

	@media (max-width: 840px) {
		.hero {
			padding-top: 3.25rem;
		}

		.feature-grid,
		.split-section,
		.bands,
		.quick-start {
			grid-template-columns: 1fr;
		}

		.split-section,
		.bands,
		.quick-start,
		.formal-section,
		.cta-section {
			padding: 2.75rem 0;
		}
	}
</style>
